    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-07-26T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-07-26T06:00:00-05:00" n="189"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d189">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.4061 Motion Pictures/216: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Marriner</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-07-26T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 26, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received July 26—10:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>633. Reference Embassy’s telegram No. 602, July 17, 5 p.m., this year. Today’s
                        <hi rend="italic">Journal Officiel</hi> contains a decree dated July 25
                    putting into effect project for detaxation of cinemas and other amusements. It
                    is gratifying to note that the decree omits the Lafont amendment or any other
                    provision discriminatory against foreign films. Please repeat to Commerce.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marriner</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
